{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522316"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:43:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:43:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13821"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13821"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.08,0.25,0.01,0.34]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6438"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83087"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6438"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13821"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68149"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1387"},{"type":"tags","id":"2385"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8340"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12716"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12717"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28432"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44963"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83087"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a two-day history of pain, redness, and swelling of her left ear. She reports accidentally hitting her ear on a door frame two days ago. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. The left ear is erythematous, tender, and swollen, particularly affecting the upper portion of the pinna (Image). The earlobe is spared. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral ciprofloxacin","Topical hydrocortisone cream","Incision and drainage","Oral acyclovir","Watchful waiting"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic signs of perichondritis, an infection of the cartilage of the outer ear, likely triggered by recent blunt trauma. A key distinguishing feature is the sparing of the earlobe, which helps differentiate perichondritis from cellulitis. Since the earlobe lacks cartilage, perichondritis primarily affects the cartilage-containing structures of the pinna, whereas cellulitis typically involves the soft tissues, including the earlobe. This distinction is important for guiding appropriate antibiotic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate initial management is \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral ciprofloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E, which provides coverage against \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E, the most common causative organisms. Prompt antibiotic treatment is crucial to prevent cartilage necrosis and subsequent ear deformity. In more severe cases or if the patient is systemically unwell, broader spectrum antibiotics or intravenous antibiotics may be necessary. However, for this patient who appears well, oral ciprofloxacin is appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical hydrocortisone cream\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as it may worsen the infection and is not effective against bacterial infections. Steroids are contraindicated in untreated infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncision and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for perichondritis unless there is a clear abscess formation, which is not evident in this case. Unnecessary incision could potentially spread the infection and damage the cartilage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral acyclovir\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiviral medication used for herpes infections. It would not be effective against the bacterial infection causing perichondritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWatchful waiting\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for perichondritis as delayed treatment can lead to serious complications including cartilage necrosis and permanent deformity of the ear (\u0027cauliflower ear\u0027). Prompt antibiotic treatment is essential.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Perichondritis is an infection of the cartilage of the outer ear, often caused by trauma or piercings.","Perichondritis requires prompt antibiotic treatment to prevent cartilage necrosis and deformity."],"references":["Perichondritis of the Pinna. In: The Royal Victorian Eye and Ear Hospital Emegency Department [online]. 2021. Available at: https://eyeandear.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Perichondritis-of-the-Pinna-Clinical-Practice-Guideline.pdf","Rivera-Morales M, Rodriguez-Belen J, Vera A, Ganti L. Perichondritis: Not all Ear pain is otitis. Cureus. 2020;12(10): Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7686808/","Wu J, Collins N, Wilson S. Perils pf pinna piercing and pseudomonas perichondritis. American Family Physician. 2003;32(7). Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/0040f5c6-78c7-431c-b57e-e4d238c85cd7/attachment.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68149"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13821"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20768"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20768"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/CpUexeGu3KpSaF55H2wPWYo5d2otLw.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/CpUexeGu3KpSaF55H2wPWYo5d2otLw.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":768,"height":1024}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68149"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-01T23:47:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-01T23:48:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6438"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83087"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemC